{"/service/ndnp/cohi/batch_cohi_ironton_ver01/data/sn90051068/00513680855/1913100401/0787.xml":{"full_text":"p\u2014 s e S L AR\nMonte Vista Lumber Company\nC. N. SHAKESPEARE, Manager\ne\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\nw e Strive for And can supply you with\n0 the best grades of LUMBER\nRel]able Semce to be had in this market, with\n\u2014_\u2014\u2014\u2014 prompt efficient attention to\nyour wants.\nStocks we carry for You\nAll Kinds of Lumber Saiurated Felt\nCoopered Lime Ruberine Root Paint\nHydrated Lime Metal Lath\nConcrete Cement Ounk and Bass wood Plate Rail\nAlkali-proof Cement Pictu ~.M mH.\nture oulding\nRed Cedar and Mex. Lath\nAGENTS FOR THE Bulldog Plaster\nh Ruberoid Roofing\nweyer aeuser Malthoid Roofing\ni S. N. Rubber Roofing\nSIIO (_)neplec____e_s_tie Elaterite 'lb:;liug\nPLANING MILL IN CONNECTION\nAll Kinds Custom Work Promptly Attended To\no e eSe TR\nQ) (k\n\nb at-13\nXl K\u00ae\n_ e(\u2018)@ C\nC. H. AKERS, Manager\nMonte Vista, Colorado\nTHE\nMonte Vista Milling Elevator\nC 0 m pa n y R. G. BRECKENRIDGE, Manager I\nWholesale Dealers In\nFlour, Hay and Grain\nw\nHome of the Other Brands:\nFamous \u201cPANSY\u201d Flour \u201cRoyal Flush\u201d *\u201cDiamond\u201d\nThe C Sil\nHaving made an exhaustive study of the\nSilo question before deciding on the one best\nbel, we came to an easy conclusi()n when we\nfound the CROWN Silo.\nIt is an exclusive silo, no other silo com\nparing with it.\nC used exclusively by the\n\\\u2014_\u2014be Crown Stave CROWN Silo, makes it\nworth more than the other Silos, let alone the many\nother advantages it has over them.\nBut the best thing about the CROWN\nSilo is we are selling you a better Silo for\nless money.\nCall and be convinced.\nMcKUNE WALLACE\nAt The National Capitol\nDOINGS OF\nThe Extraordinary Session\nThis has been a bad- year for\npolitical prophets. A Democratic\nPresident sits in the White House.\nthe Democratic House and Senate\nare at work in the Capitol redeem\ning Democratic pledges, and Dem\nocratic Governors and Legislatures\ncontrol the destinies of two-thirds\nof the states, Despite this appal\nling state of affairs, the wheels of\nindustry continue to whirl and the\ncountry proceeds serenely on its\nway\u2014prosperous and apparently\ncontented.\nThe erstwhile despised party ofi\nJefferson and Jackson has revisedi\nthe tariff\u2014revised it downward,\ntoo, don't forget that\u2014is muking\u2018\nover the country's banking and\ncurrency system, is emerging froux\u2018\nthe Mexican embroglio without\nhaving fired a shot, has knocked\n\u201cDollar Diplomacy\u201d into a cocked\nhat, has transformed Japan from a\nmenacing enemy into somethiugj\nvery like a cordial friend, has set\ntled the most serious labor disturb\nance which has threatened the rail\nroads of the country in recent\nyears, and by providing money\nneeded to move the crops has\ntaken a long step in the direction\nof destroying Wall Street\u2019s poweri\nto injure the legitimate business\ninterests of the nation.\nAnd yet we have not had si\npanic!\nIs it any wonder the prophets\u2019\nstock is way below par?\nSITUATION AT HOME 1\nHere in Colorado the prophets\nof evil have been particularly vo\nciferous. They have assured the\npeople that tariff revision meant\nindustrial stagnation. Some of\nthe Sugar Trust\u2019s papers have even\npredicted a return of the distress\ning times which followed the panic\nof '93.\nNow, I am not one of those who\nseriously contend that the pros.\nperity of the nation is altogether\ndependent upon the success of a\ncertain political party. However,\nI insist that if the Democracy is\nto be held responsible for all the\nfloods, the pestilence, the crop fail\nures and the other untoward events\nwhich may mark its lease of power\nit is only fair to give it credit for\nsome of the good things which\n\u2019oume to the people during the\u2018\nsame time.\nI have spent three weeks in Col\norado, and have bad unusual op-\u2018\nportunities to observe conditions\nTo my mind, the future never:\nseemed more hopeful. I believe\nthe state is entering on era of\ngood times.\nWe have passed through a period\nlof lean years. We have all felt\nthe stringency but some sections\nluf the state have suffered more\nitlmn others, and the Capital City\nmore than any. How absurd it\n.wmnld be to say that our troubles\nwere traceable to the fact that a\n]\u2018l(upublicuu occupied the White\nHouse during the hard times, and\nhow puerile would be the claim\nlthut the return of prosperity was\ndue to the election of a Democrat!\nOf course, if the facts could be\n}ruvcranl we would be told that the\nDemocrats were responsible for the\n|crop failures, and that prosperity\nwas the smiling hand maiden who\nwaited on the G O, P, and refused\nto respond to the call of any other\nmaster.\nAs 1 have frequently stated in\nthese letters the history of our\ncountry proves beyond cavil that\n\u2018l no panic was ever caused by tariff\nrevision. It well that the country\nand the state are receiving new and\nconvineing evidence to support\nthat statement. It will serve to\ndiscredit political pettifoggers and\nEDWARD\nKEATING\nCongressman from\nColorado\n}ennble the mass of the voters to\ntake a saner view of the economic\n\u2018problems.\nA FEW PROSPERITY ITEMS\nNaturally, as I have traveled\n\u2018through Colorado I have inquired\nclosely into the possible effect on\nbusiness of the changes in our\ntariff laws, and the information I\nhave secured has been at once in\nteresting and gratifying.\nsee you fellows in Congress\nhave placed cattle and meat on the\nfree list,\u201d said a stockman to me\nthe other day as we chatted in the\nsmoking compartment of a train\nbound for Pueblo.\n\u201cYes,\u201d lanswered. \u201cHow do\nyou think it will atfect you?\u201d\n\u201cBy George, I was nervous for\nawhile,\u201d he responded, \u201cbut I have\njust come from the Denver stock\nyards and 1 find that cattle are\ncommanding the highest price\never known at the yards in the\nmonth of September. I guess we\ncan stand a good deal of that kind\nof free trade.\u201d\nTHE BLIGHTED SUGAR INDUSTRY\nSoon after reaching the statc I\nreceived an invitation to assist in\ncelebrating the completion of the\nrailroad between Monte Vista and\nCenter in the SBan Luis Valley.\n\u201cWe had to have the road in\norder to secure a supply of beets\nfor our sugar factory at Monte\nVista,\u201d one of the promoters told\nme. \u2018\u201cWhy, I thought free sugar\nwould close all the sugar factories\nin Colorado,\u201d 1 said. *\u201cAt least\nthat is the impression I received\nfrom reading the newspaper organs\nof the sugar interest.\u201d \u2018Well,\u201d he\nreplied,\"\u201cwe are taking our chances\u201d\nI found that the capital for the\nrond was furnished by Colorado\nmen who have made their fortunes\nin the West and are familiar with\nconditions in Colorado. In the\nfinancial world they are regarded\nas \u201c\u2018conservatives\u201d and no one be-\nAphorisms of Lady Grant.\nIt is such a relief to \u201clet go,\u201d as my\naunt said when she gave up keeping\na waist! Women find a man dull and\nuninteresting when he proposes to\nanother woman, \u201cThe Chequer\nBoard,\u2019 by Lady Sibil Grant,\nExercise\nThere may be courtesy, there may\nbe even temper and wit and talent and\nsparkling conversation, there may be\ngood will, even, and yet the human\nest and divinest faculties pine for ex\nercise.\u2014~Thoreau.\nIt Makes a Difference.\nLittle Willle\u2014\"Say, pa, what is\nbusiness courtesy?\u201d Pa-\u2014\" There are\ntwo kinds of business courtesy, my\nson. One I 8 the kind extended to\npeople who pay cash, and the other\nIs extend\u00abd to people who don't.'\u2014\nStray Storifes.\nThe Value of Good Manners.\nManners must adorn knowledge and\nsmooth its way through the world,\nLike a great rough diamond, it may\ndo very well In closet byway of\ncurfosity, and also for Its Intrinsio\nvalue; but it will never be worn, nor\nshine If 4t Is not polished.\nClassical Music.\n\u201cWhat {8 your idea of classical mu\nafe?\" \u201cWell,\u201d replied Mr. Cumrox, *\u201c1\ndon\u2019t profess to know much about it.\nBut It always seems to me that when\na man writes classical music he sim\nply takes a tune and sees how much\nhe can muss it up.\u201d\nAvold Sedative Cough Medicines\nIf you want to contribute directly to\nthe occurrence of capillary bronchitis\naud pooumonia use cough medicines\nthat contain codine, morphine, heroio\nand other sedatives when you have a\ncough or cold. An expectorant like\nChamberlain\u2019s Cough Remedy is what is\nneeded. That cleans out the culture\nbeds or breeding places for the germs of\npoeumonia and other germ diseases.\nThat is why pneumonia never results\nfrom a cold when Chamberlain's Cough\nRemedy is used, It has a world.-wide\nreputation for its cures. It contains no\nmorphine or other sedative. For sale\nby all dealers\nlieves they would sink their money\nin a \u201cblighted industry.\u201d That\nthey are not alone in their faith is\nshown by the costly improvements\njust completed at the Rocky Ford\nSugar Factory by the American\nBeet Sugar Co., and by the] an\nnouncement that the ocompany\ncontroling the Sugar City factory\nhas increased the priceof sugar beet\nland 50 an acre. \u2018\u2018Paralyzed in\ndustries\u201d do not give these evi\ndences of virility,\nA manufacturer of syrups called\non me at my hotel in Denver to in\ndorse my position on the sugar\ntariff,\n\u201cColorado should supply the\nnation with syrups and preserves,\u201d\nhe declared. *\u201cWe make the sugar\nand we grow the fruit. All we re\nquire is to be freed from the grip\nof the sugar trust. As it is now,\nI can buy Colorado sugar for less\nin Chicago than I can in Denver,\nand if it were not for the fact that\nI love this state I would move my\nplant to some point on the Great\nLakes.\nFARMERS NEEDN'T WORRY\n\u201cI am told that the sugar inter\nests are threatening to out the\nprice paid the farmers for their\nbeets. Do you think they will do\nthat?\u201d I asked Senator John Cross\n'me of the prominent farmers and\nsubstantiul hosiness men of North\nern Colorado. \u201c[Don\u2019t worry about\nthe farmers,\u201d he replied. \u201cThey\nwill take care of themselves. If\nthe factories cut the price we won't\nraise the beets. We can and will\nraise other crops. The sugar men\nknow that and while they may\nbluff for public effect they will not\ncut off their noses to spite their\nfaces.\u201d\nAn old friend, the manager of\none of Denver's largest depart\nment stores greeted me on 16th\nstreet. He had written me a num\nber of letters pointing out the dire\nful results which would follow\n\u201ctariff tinkering.\u201d\n\u201cHow\u2019s business?\" I asked, brac\ning myself for a tale of business\ndisnsters, present and prospective.\n\u201cFine,\u201d was the cherry reply.\n\u201cThings are looking up. I believe\nthe old state is getting on its feet\nagain.\u201d\n\u201cBut\u2014free sugar,\u201d I protested.\n\u201cWell\u2014\" he hesitated. *\u201cOh, I\nstill think you went pretty strong\nbut\u2014. Oh, let's go and get a\ncigar.\u201d\nBOOM IN CABBAGES\nI rode through Brighton the\nother day and saw the farmers\ncoming in with great wagon loads\nof cabbages. \u2018\u201c\u2018Making any money\n\u2018this year?\u201d I asked one husky chap.\nHe grinned down at me. \u2018Say,\n\u2018panlner, when I sell these cab\n'bages I will have more money than\nsome people have hay. lam get\n\u2018ling seven times as much for them\na8 1 did last year.\u201d\n\u201cMy dear fellow,\u201d 1 said, \u201cthere\n\u2018must be some mistake. Don't you\nknow that the Democrats have just\n\u2018passed a tariff bill which is de\n\u2018signed to drive most of you farm\n\u2018\u00ab-rs to the poorhouse. My recol\nilocti()n is that they even put cab\nbages on the free list.\u201d He looked\nat me curiously as though ques\ntioping my sanity. Then he quietly\ngathered up his reins, spoke mean\ningly to his horses and drove off\ntoward the station. He looked\nback once or twice, and I could see\nthat he was in doubt whether to\nlaugh at me or turn me over to\nthe police to be returned to the\nsanitarium from which he thought\nI had wandered.\nThe farmer has been the \u201cgoat\u201d\nof protection for a long time, but\nhis eyes are opened at last,\nI will remain in Colorado until\nOctober Ist, in order to attend\nsome good roads meetings and\nwill then return to Washington,\nI do not expect to get home again\nuntil next June or July,","height":"20536","width":"12804"}}
